(1793, '_transient_feed_88c95ea6746a99025a514512c65189e8', 'a:4:{s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:3:"rss";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:3:"\n\n\n";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:7:"version";s:3:"2.0";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:7:"channel";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:55:"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n	";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:12:"Advanced Ads";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:25:"https://wpadvancedads.com";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:26:"Advanced Ads for WordPress";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:13:"lastBuildDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 12 Oct 2016 14:16:25 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"language";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5:"en-US";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:9:"generator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:30:"https://wordpress.org/?v=4.6.1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"item";a:12:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"How to add ads to a masonry layout?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:41:"https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-masonry/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 12 Oct 2016 08:56:58 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=34134";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:336:"<p>Including ads into a masonry grid is tough. It is possible with Advanced Ads though. Find the answer in this tutorial.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-masonry/">How to add ads to a masonry layout?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3283:"<p>A masonry layout is a great way to display images in a beautiful grid, even when they have different sizes. It is very common among photography blogs to use a theme which has this feature. You can see some examples on the <a href="http://masonry.desandro.com/">Masonry</a> page.</p>\n<p>However nice it looks, including ads into a masonry grid is not as easy as it might sound. I got asked for a solution a lot and finally had the chance to dig a bit deeper and come up with a way how to solve this with Advanced Ads.</p>\n<h2>Why don’t ads properly display in a masonry grid?</h2>\n<p>Masonry layouts are normally implemented using a JavaScript library. One of the most common libraries for this is <a href="http://masonry.desandro.com/">Masonry by David DeSandro</a>. It is also included in WordPress already and developers only need to activate it.</p>\n<p>The way this and other scripts are working is that they take a set of containers, get their sizes and then reorder them dynamically. All considered elements need to have the same selector. If one of them, like the ad container, does not have this selector – normally in form of a class – it is not considered in the grid and either displays completely outside the grid or is hidden beneath it.</p>\n<h2>How to consider ads in a masonry layout?</h2>\n<p>Based on the explanation above, adding an ad to the layout is actually rather simple.</p>\n<p>You only need to find out which selector is used in the theme to find all elements that need to be considered. In a recent example it was just a list of posts and the class each post container had was <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">recent-post</pre> .</p>\n<p>I then just took this class and added it to the ad container. The option for this can be found on the ad edit screen in the <em>Layout / Output</em> meta box. Simply add the class name to it like on the image below.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-34136" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class.png" alt="container class setting" width="529" height="64" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class.png 529w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class-300x36.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class-60x7.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/container-class-150x18.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 529px) 100vw, 529px" /></p>\n<p>In order to find the correct class you need to ask the theme developer or take a look into the theme’s source code where the masonry script is initialized. For the Masonry script it might look like this:</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">$(''.grid'').masonry({\r\nitemSelector: ''.recent-post'',\r\ncolumnWidth: 200\r\n});</pre><p>\n<p>Adding the ad to the page with the masonry layout is another question. If this is a list of posts, you can use the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/placement-post-lists/">Post Lists placement</a> or you can use the PHP function to include it into your theme manually.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/ads-on-masonry/">How to add ads to a masonry layout?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:40:"Inheriting ad settings to a group of ads";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:49:"https://wpadvancedads.com/inheriting-ad-settings/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 21 Sep 2016 15:15:35 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=31115";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:313:"<p>This tutorial is about inheriting settings for ads to multiple ads or an ad group.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/inheriting-ad-settings/">Inheriting ad settings to a group of ads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3129:"<p>A repeated question in support is how one can use the same conditions for multiple ads at the same time instead of managing them for each ad individually. This is especially useful when using ad groups that need a general layout adjustment or when all ads have the same visitor or display conditions.</p>\n<h2>Using the Ad Group ad type</h2>\n<p>While it is not possible to set visitor or display conditions for a group or placement directly, you can use the <em>Ad Group</em> <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/ad-types/">ad type</a> to accomplish this.</p>\n<p>The setup basically looks like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>you group the inheriting ads into the same ad group</li>\n<li>you create an intermediate ad with the <em>Ad Group</em> ad type</li>\n<li>you assign the group to that ad</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When using the <em>Ad Group</em> ad type, the ad parameters of the intermediate ad show this option:</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-31116" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select.png" alt="ad group select field" width="407" height="50" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select.png 407w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select-300x37.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select-60x7.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/ad-group-select-150x18.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 407px) 100vw, 407px" /></p>\n<p>You can now assign any parameters, display or visitor conditions to the intermediate ad.</p>\n<p>Displaying the intermediate ad works exactly like every other ad. In addition to normal ad output, it will display the group according to the group settings (random, multiple ads, etc.).</p>\n<h2>More scenarios</h2>\n<p>Here are some more ideas for when to use the <em>Ad Group</em> ad type setup.</p>\n<h3>Rotate ad groups</h3>\n<p>With the setup above, you can also rotate ad groups. Just create an intermediate ad for each group and put those into another group.</p>\n<h3>Track all ads together</h3>\n<p>You can set up <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/">tracking</a> information for a whole group so that the impressions and clicks for all ads are tracked together. This makes it also easier to set up multiple ads with the same target url.</p>\n<h2>Limitations</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>The intermediate ad can not be added to the ad group it is displaying, or else it might create an infinite loop. This should not be possible programmatically, but still good to know.</li>\n<li>Setting different conditions within the individual ads in the group compared to those in the intermediate ad might lead to unexpected behavior.</li>\n<li>Visitor conditions of the individual ads within the selected group only work on cached sites when using <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/cache-busting/">cache-busting</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/inheriting-ad-settings/">Inheriting ad settings to a group of ads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"Refresh ads on the same spot";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"https://wpadvancedads.com/refresh-ads-on-the-same-spot/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 20 Jul 2016 10:05:16 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=25899";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:288:"<p>How to refresh ads on the same spot without reloading the page.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/refresh-ads-on-the-same-spot/">Refresh ads on the same spot</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2478:"<p>In order use an existing placement for multiple ads or to fight ad blindness, you can rotate ads on the same spot during the same page impression.</p>\n<p>In Advanced Ads, this is possible with two features:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>refresh on the next page impression using ad groups</li>\n<li>using the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/slider/">Ad Slider add-on</a></li>\n<li>using the refresh option in <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Ad rotation in Advanced Ads Pro</h2>\n<p>With <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a>, you have the additional option of enabling a refresh interval for random and ordered ad groups.</p>\n<p>In order to use that feature, you need to enable the cache-busting module in <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; Pro</em>.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-25900" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval.png" alt="ad refresh interval option" width="441" height="75" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval.png 441w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval-300x51.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval-60x10.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ad-refresh-interval-150x26.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 441px) 100vw, 441px" /></a></p>\n<p>Just enable the option and set the time for the refresh in milliseconds.</p>\n<p>The ads will then be reloaded automatically.</p>\n<p>If you are using the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/">Tracking add-on</a>, the impression will be counted once per page and only, if the ad really showed up.</p>\n<h2>What else you need to know</h2>\n<p>The number of visible ads at the same time is limited to one, when the ad refresh is enabled.</p>\n<p>Counting impressions for ad refreshes like this is taking some performance, since every call to an ad is loading parts of WordPress. The impact of multiple ad rotations per page set up like above on your server should be monitored by a server admin.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/refresh-ads-on-the-same-spot/">Refresh ads on the same spot</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:36:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:58:"How to split-test different ad positions (Placement Tests)";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:67:"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 20 Jul 2016 09:47:31 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=25882";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:385:"<p>With Advanced Ads Pro you can run tests based on the position of the ad by rotating the placements against each other.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/">How to split-test different ad positions (Placement Tests)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3976:"<p>With <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> you can run tests based on the position of the ad. This feature can serve various purposes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>test ads in position A against ads in position B</li>\n<li>rotation different or the same ad to fight ad blindness</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Position tests are running through the placements interface, which you can find unter <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em>.</p>\n<h3>Creating a split test</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> in your site’s dashboard.</li>\n<li>Select a <em>Test weight</em> for the placements you want to test against each other (see below). There is no limit on the number of placements included in a test.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure id="attachment_25884" style="width: 148px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="size-full wp-image-25884" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/test-weight.png" alt="test weight setting" width="148" height="47" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/test-weight.png 148w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/test-weight-60x19.png 60w" sizes="(max-width: 148px) 100vw, 148px" /><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Select the weight for the placement in the test.</figcaption></figure>\n<ol start="3">\n<li>Click on Save New Test.</li>\n<li>The test is now active and should show up in the Placement tests section above all placements.</li>\n<li>After creating a placement test, you can set an expiry date and define an email address to which a short notice is being sent. The expiry date does not remove the test. This option is checked once per day, so the email might be sent with some delay.</li>\n</ol>\n<figure id="attachment_25886" style="width: 746px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-25886" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests.png" alt="Placement tests overview" width="746" height="155" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests.png 746w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-300x62.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-60x12.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/placement-tests-150x31.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 746px) 100vw, 746px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Placement tests overview</figcaption></figure>\n<h3>Test weight</h3>\n<p>Test weights work like <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/rotate-ad/">ad rotation weights</a>. E.g., If you set a weight of 2 for Placement A and 4 for Placement B, Placement B will show up twice as often as Placement A.</p>\n<p>Placements show up randomly, i.e. the same placement can show up multiple times in a row before switched to another placement.</p>\n<h3>Evaluating ad tests</h3>\n<p>Unless you are using the test feature to fight ad blindness with random ad positions, you might want to compare the positions with each other.</p>\n<p>In order to do that, you should show different ads for each placement.</p>\n<p>If you run an ad network like AdSense, create different AdSense ad units for the test. You can then use the reports in AdSense to see which ad performed best.</p>\n<p>If you are testing in-house ads, custom code or images, you can use the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/">Tracking add-on</a> to track impressions and clicks.</p>\n<h3>What else you need to know</h3>\n<p>In order to test different ads on the same position, you should use an <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/rotate-ad/">ad rotation</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-split-test-different-ad-positions/">How to split-test different ad positions (Placement Tests)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:35:"Displaying Ads with Visual Composer";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"https://wpadvancedads.com/visual-composer-ads/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 16 Jun 2016 08:30:38 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=22134";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:555:"<p>Visual Composer by WPBakery is one of the most popular premium page builder for WordPress. No wonder, that I receive many requests on how to use ads, and especially AdSense ad units, directly within the Visual Composer interface. Until now, the simple solution was to use a shortcode from an ad, group or placement created [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/visual-composer-ads/">Displaying Ads with Visual Composer</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6027:"<p>Visual Composer by WPBakery is one of the most popular premium page builder for WordPress. No wonder, that I receive many requests on how to use ads, and especially AdSense ad units, directly within the Visual Composer interface.</p>\n<p>Until now, the simple solution was to use a shortcode from an ad, group or placement created with Advanced Ads and put it into the text element provided by Visual Composer. However, finding it again among other text elements was a challenge to some users.</p>\n<a class="st-btn large st-btn-blue st-btn-large" href="https://downloads.wordpress.org/plugin/ads-for-visual-composer.1.0.zip" target="_self">Download the Visual Composer Add-On</a>\n<h2>Advanced Ads and Visual Composer</h2>\n<p>If you are not a user of Advanced Ads yet, you should take a look at the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/features/">powerful features</a> it provides.</p>\n<p>Visual Composer by WPBakery is a premium page builder for WordPress. Instead of writing all your texts and use shortcodes in the editor WordPress provides, Visual Composer replaces that text area with an interface consisting widget-like elements. Those elements can be individually configured, allowing you to build detailed pages with various features. You can even edit pages in the frontend and see how they change live.</p>\n<h2>Visual Composer Ads add-on</h2>\n<p>With the increasing demand, I build an add-on to integrate Advanced Ads and Visual Composer. You can <a href="https://wordpress.org/plugins/ads-for-visual-composer/">download it for free from wordpress.org</a>.</p>\n<p>Once installed and activated, the add-on you should find three new Visual Composer elements in the editor:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Advanced Ads – Ad</li>\n<li>Advanced Ads – Group</li>\n<li>Advanced Ads – Placement</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There is also a new tab called <em>Ads</em> with these elements.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22135" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements.png" alt="Visual Composer Ad Elements Tab" width="769" height="149" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements.png 769w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-300x58.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-60x12.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ad-elements-150x29.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 769px) 100vw, 769px" /></a></p>\n<h2>Where to find the ID?</h2>\n<p>When you add and open one of the widgets, you will find an input field for an id of the ad element.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22136" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box.png" alt="Visual Composer Ads Box" width="338" height="263" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box.png 338w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box-300x233.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box-60x47.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/visual-composer-ads-box-150x117.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 338px) 100vw, 338px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Ad ID</h3>\n<p>Open the ad edit screen and stop the Wizard, if active. You should now see the Ad ID below the ad title.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22137" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id.png" alt="Ad ID field" width="325" height="80" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id.png 325w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id-300x74.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id-60x15.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/ad-id-150x37.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 325px) 100vw, 325px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Group ID</h3>\n<p>The Group ID is listed in the details column of the ad group list.<a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22138" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id.png" alt="Ad Group ID field" width="381" height="64" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id.png 381w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id-300x50.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id-60x10.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/group-id-150x25.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 381px) 100vw, 381px" /></a></p>\n<h3>Placement ID</h3>\n<p>Create a <em>Manual</em> placement. Open the list of placements and click on <em>show usage</em> below the placement’s name. Extract the ID from the id attribute in the shortcode field.</p>\n<p>In the screenshot below, the placement ID is &#8220;theme-header&#8221;.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-22139" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id.png" alt="Ad Placement ID" width="502" height="155" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id.png 502w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id-300x93.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id-60x19.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/placement-id-150x46.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 502px) 100vw, 502px" /></a></p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/visual-composer-ads/">Displaying Ads with Visual Composer</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:5:{s:0:"";a:7:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"Displaying alternative content to ad block users";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:75:"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:84:"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 02 May 2016 09:55:59 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:14:"Update Notices";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=16891";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:558:"<p>When an ad block user visits your site, he might not see the ad you have prepared for them, but instead see a blank spot. This is a challenge all publishers face and therefore it is the most popular feature request for Advanced Ads right now. I am going to address this issue as soon [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/">Displaying alternative content to ad block users</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2336:"<p>When an ad block user visits your site, he might not see the ad you have prepared for them, but instead see a blank spot. This is a challenge all publishers face and therefore it is the most popular feature request for Advanced Ads right now.</p>\n<p>I am going to address this issue as soon as possible, but in order to do it right, I wanted to ask you for your feedback regarding two important questions.</p>\n<h2>Where to set the alternative content?</h2>\n<p>Advanced Ads has three structural elements: ads, groups and placements. For a better usability, I will only add the option to enter content displayed to ad block users for one of these structural elements. Which one, is still open for discussion. I only believe that it doesn’t make sense on a group level, since many users don’t actually use or need them, but maybe I am wrong.</p>\n<p>Please vote for the level on which you would like to be able to select the content displayed to ad blockers in the following poll:</p>\nNote: There is a poll embedded within this post, please visit the site to participate in this post''s poll.\n<p>If you have another idea, please share it in the comments below.</p>\n<h2>Choosing another “ad” or custom input?</h2>\n<p>The second question is whether there should be a plain input field for the ad blocker content or you want to actually select another “ad” to be displayed, when ad blockers are activated.</p>\n<p>Of course, the alternative ad needs to be undetectable, like custom html code or an image not named “banner” or so, but especially when you want to reuse the alternative ad blocker content, this seems to be a flexible option.</p>\n<p>Please select your favorite option below:</p>\nNote: There is a poll embedded within this post, please visit the site to participate in this post''s poll.\n<p>If you have another idea, please share it in the comments below.</p>\n<p>Please note, that I am only going to accept comments regarding this post. If you have a support question, please <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/support/">contact me through support</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/">Displaying alternative content to ad block users</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:80:"https://wpadvancedads.com/displaying-alternative-content-to-ad-block-users/feed/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";a:1:{s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"4";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"How to enable Page-level ads";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:55:"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Thu, 28 Apr 2016 08:16:34 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=16551";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:299:"<p>How to activate Page-level ads on your WordPress site with just one click.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/">How to enable Page-level ads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3216:"<p>In April 2016, AdSense enabled the new Page-level ads for all its users. If you were wondering how to monetize mobile traffic more efficiently, this might be the answer.</p>\n<p>Advanced Ads has a feature embedded that allows you to implement Page-level ads into your site with just one click. While you find the tutorial below, you can check out my <a href="http://webgilde.com/en/adsense-page-level-ads-test/">review on Page-level ads</a> in order to learn if this is worth a try or not.</p>\n<h2>How to implement Page-level ads</h2>\n<h3>Enabling Page-level ads in your AdSense account</h3>\n<p>Before using Page-level ads on your site, you need to go to your AdSense account and activate them.</p>\n<p>You’ll find them under <em>My Ads &gt; Content &gt; Page-level ads</em>.</p>\n<p>Page-level ads come in two formats. As <em>Anchor/overlay ads</em> which are very similar to our Sticky ads, but only sticky at the bottom of the page on mobile devices.</p>\n<p>Vignette ads are rather a full overlay, much like our <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/popup-and-layer-ads/">PopUp Ads</a>. Both formats are only working on high end mobile devices and not showing up on every page impression. They also don’t count for the 3-ads-per-page limit.</p>\n<figure id="attachment_16552" style="width: 598px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/page-level-ads/" rel="attachment wp-att-16552"><img class="size-full wp-image-16552" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads.png" alt="Page-level ads types" width="598" height="325" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads.png 598w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads-300x163.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads-60x33.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/page-level-ads-150x82.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 598px) 100vw, 598px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Page-level Ads settings with Vignette Ads enabled</figcaption></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Implement Page-level Ads in your WordPress site</h2>\n<p>Once you activated at least one of the ad formats, you should switch to your WordPress dashboard and navigate to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; AdSense</em>.</p>\n<p>If you didn’t include your AdSense ID, now is a good time to do that. You can find details about it <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/adsense-ads/">here</a>.</p>\n<p>Now, you only need to activate the <em>Activate Page-Level ads</em> option and save the settings and the ad tag will be implemented on your site.</p>\n<h3>Test the Page-level ad tag</h3>\n<p>Since ads only show up occasionally on mobile, you can go back to the Page-level ad page in your AdSense account, scroll down and use the <em>Test it out</em> button to test if the Page-level tag is implemented. If not, please review the settings again or update your cache.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-to-enable-page-level-ads/">How to enable Page-level ads</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:61:"Manage revenue share on multi-author blogs – ads per author";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:69:"https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-revenue-share-on-mulit-author-blogs/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 09 Mar 2016 15:45:11 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=12616";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:379:"<p>How to display ads based on the post’s author and create a revenue share model with authors on your blog.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-revenue-share-on-mulit-author-blogs/">Manage revenue share on multi-author blogs – ads per author</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3957:"<p>A very popular feature request was to allow a revenue share with authors. For example, on an ad position within posts, you could show the author’s ad 20% of the time and 80% the ads from the publisher. This would allow authors to earn more from successful posts and also motive them to create more attention to their posts.</p>\n<p>After thinking about this for a while, I decided against adding a specific feature. Especially since version 1.7 of Advanced Ads has a display conditions that allows to display ads only on posts from a specific author.</p>\n<h2>1. Create ad units</h2>\n<p>The easiest solution for a revenue share with authors would be to create ad units for each author. These ads could either be from your own ad networks (AdSense, or whatever program you are using) or you could get the ads from your authors, in case they have their own accounts.</p>\n<p>You also need to create the ads that show up for your account.</p>\n<h2>2. Set the <em>Author</em> Display Condition</h2>\n<p>In order to attach a specific ad to an author, you must use the <em>Author</em> Display Condition. Once you added it in the <em>Display Conditions</em> meta box, you can select the author to which this ad “belongs”. This will make sure, that the ad will only show up on posts where this user is the author.</p>\n<figure id="attachment_12619" style="width: 435px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition.png" rel="attachment wp-att-12619"><img class="size-full wp-image-12619" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition.png" alt="author display condition with Thomas selected" width="435" height="41" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition.png 435w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition-300x28.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition-60x6.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-display-condition-150x14.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 435px) 100vw, 435px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">This ad would show only on posts written by Thomas</figcaption></figure>\n<h2>3. Create a group</h2>\n<p>Now, create a new ad group from the <em>random</em> type. You might name it by the author. Assign the author’s ad and your own ad to this group. Make sure that the ad weight is set up accordingly. For a 20:80 share you would choose 2 for the author’s ad and 8 for your own. 1:4 would work too.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group.png" rel="attachment wp-att-12620"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-12620" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group.png" alt="author share group" width="180" height="139" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group-60x46.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/author-share-group-150x116.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></a></p>\n<h2>4. Implement the group</h2>\n<p>The last step is to implement the group.</p>\n<p>If you have multiple authors and want to display the ad on the same spot, you need to use a little trick.</p>\n<p>Create another ad for each group. This ad should also have the author display condition set, be of the <em>Rich Content</em> type and only the shortcode of that group in the text field.</p>\n<p>Now, create a meta group with all these intermediate ads in it and place it whereever you want.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manage-revenue-share-on-mulit-author-blogs/">Manage revenue share on multi-author blogs – ads per author</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:39:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:52:"Using AdSense and other Ads in the Genesis Framework";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:56:"https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-ads-genesis-framework/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 20 Jan 2016 14:30:24 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:11:"Genesis Ads";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Placements";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=9779";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:408:"<p>Genesis and AdSense work great together. Learn from this tutorial how Advanced Ads and the free Genesis Ads plugin can help you with an easy to use interface.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-ads-genesis-framework/">Using AdSense and other Ads in the Genesis Framework</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2617:"<p>The Genesis Framework is a very powerful tool to build great websites with WordPress. Many theme developers already build their customization on top of it. If you display ads from AdSense or other ad networks on your site, Genesis is also a great choice because it makes it simple to add and place the ad units in various positions without the need for additional coding.</p>\n<p>The reason Genesis and AdSense work so great together are hooks. They are placeholders who allow you to target specific positions for any content, not only AdSense ads.</p>\n<p>If you are interested in playing with hooks in WordPress and PHP then follow the <a href="https://www.smashingmagazine.com/2016/01/get-started-with-hooks-wordpress/" target="_blank">tutorial I wrote for Smashing Magazine</a>.</p>\n<p>In case you are less tech-savviy or just want to get the job done quickly, the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/genesis-ads/">free Genesis Ads add-on</a> for Advanced Ads makes use of that built-in technique and gives it an interface.</p>\n<p>After you created an ad you head over to the <em>Placements</em> page and create a new <em>Genesis</em> placement choosing the placement type with the following image.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-4905" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png" alt="Genesis logo" width="180" height="135" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-150x113.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></p>\n<p>Next, choose any of the positions available in the placement options. You can find a list of them through the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/genesis-ads/" target="_blank">add-on page</a>.</p>\n<p>After saving the options, your ad should be already visible.</p>\n<p>If your ad doesn’t show up then beside the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/common-issues/" target="_blank">common issues</a> it might happen that the theme you chose does not make use of all the documented hooks that normally come with the framework. In that case take a look at the other <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/placements/" target="_blank">available placements</a> in Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/adsense-ads-genesis-framework/">Using AdSense and other Ads in the Genesis Framework</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:38:"How can I apply custom CSS to my Blog?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:64:"https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 13 Jan 2016 09:53:26 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=9412";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:343:"<p>This tutorial lists different methods on how to use custom CSS rules in your blog and insert them. </p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/">How can I apply custom CSS to my Blog?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3317:"<p>Displaying ads on your site is also always an interference with the layout. You might therefore often have requirements for ad placements that can not be handles automatically with the options in Advaned Ads. In support, we might then suggest to use custom CSS rules. This tutorial explains how you can write those.</p>\n<p>This tutorial is no introduction into CSS, the language for styling websites. For basic information <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_Style_Sheets">read more on Wikipedia</a>.</p>\n<h2>Where can I insert CSS?</h2>\n<p>You have various options to insert custom CSS.</p>\n<h3>Use the style.css of your theme</h3>\n<p>Every theme comes with a style.css file. You can just add your custom CSS code there.</p>\n<p>However, this change might be overridden with the next update of a theme and other developers and users might also not find those changes easily.</p>\n<h3>Using theme options</h3>\n<p>Many professional themes come with an option to insert custom CSS or code into the head section of your website.</p>\n<p>This option can often be found within the theme option panel, which is at a different place depending on your theme. Please refer to the manual or ask the developer of the theme for guidance.</p>\n<p>These options don’t get overridden on a theme update, but of course are only bound to the current theme and don’t apply if you change it.</p>\n<h3>Using a Header Code placement in Advanced Ads</h3>\n<p>Advanced Ads itself comes with a <em>Header Code</em> placement which is intended to manage ad tags that need to be loaded in the <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">head</pre>  section of the page. However, this can also be used to inject custom CSS rules into your site and preserve them through theme updates.</p>\n<p>To create such custom code, first create an ad of the <em>Plain Text</em> ad type and wrap the css rules in <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">&lt;style&gt;…&lt;/style&gt;</pre> tags. No other settings for the “ad” are needed.</p>\n<p>Now go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> and create a Header Code placement. Assign the ad there too and save the placements to publish it.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.png" rel="attachment wp-att-2559"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2559" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.png" alt="header" width="180" height="135" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header-150x113.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></a></p>\n<h2>How can I target ads for styling?</h2>\n<p>CSS is always targeted towards a specific element in the frontend. If you need the ad to have a specific ID or CLASS parameter, insert them either in the appropriate fields in the ad settings or use a placement.</p>\n<p>Placements are automatically wrapped with a container that has a class attribute derrived from the placement title.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/how-can-i-apply-custom-css-to-my-blog/">How can I apply custom CSS to my Blog?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:10;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:33:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:34:"How to open an ad in a new window?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"https://wpadvancedads.com/open-ad-in-new-window/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 04 Jan 2016 18:49:08 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=8630";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:325:"<p>In this tutorial I will show you how you can open a link in an ad in a new window using Advanced Ads.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/open-ad-in-new-window/">How to open an ad in a new window?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:4762:"<p>Opening an ad in a new window or browser tab is a good idea if you don’t want to lose visitors entirely to the advertisers page, but still keep them on your site too.</p>\n<p>In this tutorial I will show you how you can accomplish this with Advanced Ads. It basically depends on the ad type and can also be done using an add-on.</p>\n<h2>1. Plain Text ads</h2>\n<p>If you are using the <em>Plain Text and Code</em> ad type, you can simply add some attributes to the link tag to open it in a new window.</p>\n<p>For example, change</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">&lt;a href="https://wpadvancedads.com"&gt;Anchor Text&lt;/a&gt;</pre><p>\nto</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">&lt;a href="https://wpadvancedads.com" target="_blank"&gt;Anchor Text&lt;/a&gt;</pre><p>\nThe <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">target="_blank"</pre>  attribute tells your browser to open the link in a new browser tab or window.</p>\n<p>Keep in mind that ad networks that provide ad code in JavaScript normally don’t allow you to modify the code so that it opens in a new window (e.g., AdSense doesn’t).</p>\n<h2>2. Rich Media ads</h2>\n<p>If you are using the <em>Rich Media</em> ad type, you can simply highlight a text that you want to link and click on the link icon in the toolbar. The popup that opens for you to select the link target url and the anchor text also contains a checkbox that you can enable in order to open the link in a new window / tab.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank.png" rel="attachment wp-att-8631"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-8631" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank.png" alt="open link in new window option" width="471" height="128" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank.png 471w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank-300x82.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank-60x16.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/link-text-blank-150x41.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 471px) 100vw, 471px" /></a></p>\n<h2>3. Open all or individual ads in a new window</h2>\n<p>An option that workes for all other ad types (especially Image ads) is included in the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/tracking/" target="_blank">Tracking add-on</a>.</p>\n<p>Once you have that plugin installed you can choose whether all automatically created links should open in a new window or not.</p>\n<p>Go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Settings &gt; Tracking</em> and check one of the options below.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-ad-in-new-window.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-26028 aligncenter" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-ad-in-new-window.png" alt="option to open ad in new window" width="971" height="82" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-ad-in-new-window.png 971w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-ad-in-new-window-300x25.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-ad-in-new-window-60x5.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-ad-in-new-window-150x13.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 971px) 100vw, 971px" /></a></p>\n<p>Keep in mind that only automatically created links will open in a new window. If you track with the link tag hard coded into the ad code (plain text or rich media ad type), you would still need to modify the existing link tag like described in option 1 and 2 above.</p>\n<h3>Open individual ads in a new window</h3>\n<p>The add-on also provides an option to open an individual ad in a new window.</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-single-ad-in-new-window.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-26029 aligncenter" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-single-ad-in-new-window.png" alt="option to open single ad in new window" width="447" height="64" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-single-ad-in-new-window.png 447w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-single-ad-in-new-window-300x43.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-single-ad-in-new-window-60x9.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/open-single-ad-in-new-window-150x21.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 447px) 100vw, 447px" /></a></p>\n<p>When you select <em>default</em>, the general setting will be used.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/open-ad-in-new-window/">How to open an ad in a new window?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:11;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:42:"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:46:"How to place ads in the header of your website";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:54:"https://wpadvancedads.com/place-ads-in-website-header/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Fri, 11 Dec 2015 10:24:05 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"category";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9:"Tutorials";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:16:"Advanced Ads Pro";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7:"Genesis";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Placements";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:33:"https://wpadvancedads.com/?p=7830";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:342:"<p>Four methods to place an ad into the header of your website, with or without the need to write code.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/place-ads-in-website-header/">How to place ads in the header of your website</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"Thomas";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8882:"<p>Many users asked me how they could place an ad into the upper part of their website. This article should cover all the options you currently have with Advanced Ads.</p>\n<h2>What is the website “header”?</h2>\n<p>It depends on your theme what the header really is, but one could say that it is the upper visible part of your website that doesn’t change (much) on all pages. It often contains a logo or navigation. For wpadvancedads.com, I would consider the green highlighted area on the screenshot to be the header.</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-7833 size-medium" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-300x121.png" alt="website header" width="300" height="121" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-300x121.png 300w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-768x311.png 768w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-1024x414.png 1024w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-60x24.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header-150x61.png 150w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/header.png 1150w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>“header” vs. “head”</h3>\n<p>You might sometimes need to place an ad code into the “head” part of your website. This shouldn’t be confused with the “header”. The “head” is the invisible part at the top of your website’s source code and no place for visible ads. Some ad networks or servers like DFP need to place code there that pre-loads content that is displayed later.</p>\n<h2>Methods to place an ad into the header</h2>\n<p>These are the basic methods to put an ad that is managed with Advanced Ads into the header:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>PHP function / Manual Placement</li>\n<li>Theme option</li>\n<li>Custom Position placement</li>\n<li>Genesis placements</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>1. PHP function / Manual Placement</h3>\n<p>If you are familiar with PHP and know how WordPress themes are working, you can place the ad manually into the header of your site.</p>\n<p>You can either use the function for an ad <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">the_ad()</pre>, a group <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">the_ad_group()</pre>, or a placement <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">the_ad_placement()</pre>.</p>\n<p>I personally prefer to use the <em>Manual Placement</em>, because once you set it up, it can stay there forever and you can change the ads or group that should appear there from your dashboard, without touching the source code ever again.</p>\n<p>To use the Manual Placement go to <em>Advanced Ads &gt; Placements</em> and create a new placement with the type that is represented by the following image:</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2560" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual.png" alt="manual placement" width="180" height="135" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/manual-150x113.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></p>\n<p>Choose a name that helps you remembering where you are going to place the ad and choose the ad or group that should be displayed, if you created it already.</p>\n<p>Now, open the template file with the header code in it. This is very likely the <pre class="crayon-plain-tag">header.php</pre> file in your theme folder. From there on you must find your way to the position in the code where you want to place the ad.</p>\n<p>You can get the PHP code for the placement by clicking on the <em>show usage</em> link on the placement page. However, I prefer the following extended version of that code to make sure that it doesn’t break your site if Advanced Ads is not available:</p><pre class="crayon-plain-tag">&lt;?php if( function_exists( ''the_ad_placement'' ) ){\r\nthe_ad_placement(''PLACEMENT_SLUG'');\r\n} ?&gt;</pre><p>\nBe sure to replace the second line with what you find below the <em>show usage</em> link on the placement page.</p>\n<p>Save the template file and you are ready to make use of this placement.</p>\n<h3>Child Themes</h3>\n<p>One problem you might run into with this method are updates of your theme. When you replace the changed file with a new version, your changes will be lost. So if possible, <a href="https://codex.wordpress.org/Child_Themes">create a child theme</a> for such manual changes.</p>\n<h3>2. Theme option</h3>\n<p>There are many themes out there which already provide basic ad placements and options to put content into a predefined position in the header.</p>\n<p>This varies a lot from theme to theme, so I can only give general advice here.</p>\n<p>Most important is to check, whether these fields accept shortcodes or PHP functions. If they accept shortcodes, create a Manual Placement like described above. Instead of using the PHP function that you find below the <em>show usage</em> link, get the shortcode and place it in the theme option for the header.</p>\n<p>If your theme accepts PHP code, but not a shortcode, use the PHP code from above. However, using the shortcode should always be the preferred choice.</p>\n<h3>3. Custom Position placement</h3>\n<p>The Custom Position placement lets you choose any position in your theme for your ads. It is the best way if you want to be most flexible and are not experienced with coding. It also works after theme updates.</p>\n<p>This placement comes with <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/advanced-ads-pro/">Advanced Ads Pro</a> and has this symbol:</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-3463" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position.png" alt="custom ad position placement" width="180" height="135" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/custom-position-150x113.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></p>\n<p>There is a dedicated page in the manual which also includes a video on how to use this placement:</p>\n<p><a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/manual/custom-position-placement/">Custom Position placement</a></p>\n<h3>4. Insert ads into Genesis Theme header</h3>\n<p>Many publishers are using the Genesis theme framework or a child theme built on top of this. The Genesis theme comes with many hooks that allow you to insert content on very different positions.</p>\n<p>However, not all child themes offer an interface to make use of this, so I wrote the <a href="https://wpadvancedads.com/add-ons/genesis-ads/">Genesis placement add-on</a>.</p>\n<p>This add-on offers a placement that allows you to target the hooks. There are a few header positions included too, which you can test in order to move your ad to the correct position.</p>\n<p>When choosing this option to place the ad in your websites header, just look out for this placement symbol:</p>\n<p><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-4905" src="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png" alt="Genesis logo" width="180" height="135" srcset="https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis.png 180w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-60x45.png 60w, https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-content/uploads/edd/2015/10/genesis-150x113.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 180px) 100vw, 180px" /></p>\n<h2>Is the header a good ad position?</h2>\n<p>Finally, I would like to share my opinion as a publisher and consultant about the header position with you.</p>\n<p>If you are using performance based ads (where you get paid for clicks or other actions), the header position is a sub-optimal placement. The reason is simply that people are interested in the content of your site, not the header. They also quickly learn which elements are there and don’t look at this position anymore.</p>\n<p>If you work with AdSense and check the active view stats, you might even find that this metric, showing how many times the ad was visible for a second, is quite low. The reason is that people quickly scroll down to see the real content. The smaller the device, the shorter the time spend on the header is.</p>\n<p>The more new visitors you have, the better the performance of the header ads might actually be. It is also a good position for internal ads or the ones that don’t need to be clicked in order to earn you money. In fact, some ad networks like their ads there too, despite the rather low performance.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com/place-ads-in-website-header/">How to place ads in the header of your website</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://wpadvancedads.com">Advanced Ads</a>.</p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";a:1:{s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:3:{s:4:"href";s:31:"https://wpadvancedads.com/feed/";s:3:"rel";s:4:"self";s:4:"type";s:19:"application/rss+xml";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:44:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/";a:2:{s:12:"updatePeriod";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:6:"hourly";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:15:"updateFrequency";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:1:"1";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:"type";i:128;s:7:"headers";O:42:"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary":1:{s:7:"\0*\0data";a:13:{s:4:"date";s:29:"Wed, 12 Oct 2016 15:44:48 GMT";s:6:"server";s:13:"Apache/2.4.20";s:12:"x-powered-by";s:10:"PHP/5.6.12";s:12:"x-robots-tag";s:15:"noindex, follow";s:4:"link";s:62:"<https://wpadvancedads.com/wp-json/>; rel="https://api.w.org/"";s:10:"set-cookie";a:3:{i:0;s:143:"advanced_ads_pro_visitor_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwpadvancedads.com%2Ffeed%2F; expires=Fri, 01-Jan-1971 00:00:00 GMT; Max-Age=-1444751088; path=/";i:1;s:99:"advanced_ads_page_impressions=0; expires=Sun, 30-Dec-1979 00:00:00 GMT; Max-Age=-1160927088; path=/";i:2;s:295:"edd_user_history=%5B%7B%22url%22%3A%22https%3A%5C%2F%5C%2Fwpadvancedads.com%5C%2Ffeed%5C%2F%22%2C%22time%22%3A1476287088%7D%2C%7B%22url%22%3A%22https%3A%5C%2F%5C%2Fwpadvancedads.com%5C%2Ffeed%5C%2F%22%2C%22time%22%3A1476287088%7D%5D; expires=Wed, 19-Oct-2016 15:44:48 GMT; Max-Age=604800; path=/";}s:4:"vary";s:15:"Accept-Encoding";s:13:"last-modified";s:29:"Wed, 12 Oct 2016 14:16:25 GMT";s:16:"content-encoding";s:4:"gzip";s:13:"cache-control";s:12:"max-age=3600";s:7:"expires";s:29:"Wed, 12 Oct 2016 16:44:48 GMT";s:14:"content-length";s:5:"14421";s:12:"content-type";s:34:"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8";}}s:5:"build";s:14:"20160705095230";}', 'no');
